Interestingly, in a 400-page book, Julius Evola dedicates only half a paragraph at the beginning and 2 pages at the end on homosexuality, dismissing it, as it "must wholly lack every profound dimension and meaning, because of the absence of ontological and metaphysical premises".

Examining various fetishisms of his time, he concludes some of them contain elements of deep eroticism that have turned into a perversion only after the loss of certain limitations. "No similar recognition can be given in respect to homosexuality." It's just not that interesting.
